727062f-a.text:
Jamaica Ave., (tracks thereon), at the northeast corner of 168th St., showing according to T.F. Archer, Caleb Weeks Tavern, also known as the John Plemming house.  John Plemming came from Ireland to Jamaica in 1856.  After serving in the Civil War, he became Distract Attorney for Queens County in 1883.  At a latter date he was made a judge of the Special Sessions Court.

1922

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727063f-a.text:
Jamaica Ave., (tracks thereon) north side, at, adjoining and west of 168th St., showing at the corner the Daniel Gracy house and store of 1873.  One Geis was the owner in 1891.  In 1923, the Long Island Daily Press occupied the premises.  A saloon once owned by Martin Prince and later by one Klinger also occupied this corner.  A four story brick structure was on this site in 1934.  The building in this view was erected in 1872 or 73 when a fire demolished those then standing.  The house adjoining the corner on Jamaica Ave. still stands in 1934.

March 1923

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
